      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "cd996ca316898618",
        "text": "However, the shaggy braid of social causes and effects is always intertwined with cause-effect strands, which appear to many participants as non-human and thus as non-social. Simply one says here: with natural causes. But the collective term \"nature\" for such a class of causes and effects is misleading, as soon as one believes to be able to save the sociological analysis in this respect (so that the neighboring scientists have a field for themselves1 ). However, there is no natural cause-effect sequence which is not\n- either socially defined\n- or socially excluded from the definition\nis. Both are \"social\": the inclusion and the exclusion of social definitions of \"natural\" processes. This, in turn, is the result of the fact that people relate to each other historically, that they pretend or conceal facts or assertions to each other - once or recently - that they agreed or deceived each other about their knowledge of nature and society - possibly all unconsciously. Either way - they always judge in social entanglement.\nSo, from this point of view, there is no pure \"natural\" catastrophe. Whether a snowfall is a catastrophe depends on facts that people pretend to each other (e.g., equipment), or on assertions they make (e.g., an emergency call).\nRapidly a fortiori further concluded: Even less therefore 1st our \"second nature1, the materialized relational structure of society called \"technology\" something non-social (v. BORRIES 1979). Thus, deflnitorially, there can be no pure technical catastrophe. Technical entanglements are coagulated social ones. Finally, \"war\" is not an alien-dark cause of catastrophe. It is a historically common, possibly catastrophic form of social interdependence.\nSo it is not \"nature\", \"technology\", \"war\" that cause catastrophes, breaking into the social-normal (the \"society\") from \"outside \"1 - but there are"
